":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Empty repository with no commits produces empty report instead of error","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is how actual git commands behave on a truly empty repository (no HEAD, no refs). Different git commands produce different results on empty repos (some fail, some return empty output). This is specific to real git behavior and cannot be mocked—the tool must be tested on an actual empty repository.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repository with no commits. Run the tool and verify: (1) tool exits with code 0 (success), (2) output is a valid empty report (either empty JSON object, empty list, or clearly marked 'no changes'), (3) no errors or exceptions are logged.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Report counts exactly match the actual change history of the analyzed repository","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core end-to-end correctness test. While comprehensive unit tests with mocked git output could catch some counting logic errors, real failures include git version-specific output formats, merge commit handling, special character encodings in filenames, and interactions between git commands. Only testing against a known-good repository with controlled history can verify true accuracy.","test_description":"Create a test repository with a controlled commit history: commit 1 adds 3 files, commit 2 modifies 1 file, commit 3 deletes 1 file, commit 4 renames 1 file, and includes a merge commit. Run the tool and verify the reported counts of adds, deletes, modifies, and renames exactly match the git log.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Output is identical whether analyzing staged changes, unstaged changes, or all changes","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary includes the tool's git command invocation logic and git's staging area behavior. Verifying true output identity requires manipulating git's staging area (git add, git reset) and invoking the tool in both states. Mocking git output for staged vs. unstaged scenarios cannot replicate git's actual behavior or catch subtle differences in the tool's state handling.","test_description":"Set up a real repository with both staged and unstaged changes. Run the tool once analyzing all changes, then run it again after unstaging (git reset) and re-staging in a different order. Verify the outputs are byte-for-byte identical in format and category counts.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13609,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13609},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc48281c-be06-4920-af13-29cf21bc1fb2","uuid":"23f7bda4-ac9e-4dc1-b562-d45fd5fc5d55"}
